  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Carrier Superposition.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Psi(t)=A\\cos(\\omega_1t)+B\\cos(\\omega_2t).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Envelope--Carrier Decomposition.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Psi(t)\n=\n2C\n\\cos\\left(\n\\frac{\\omega_1-\\omega_2}{2}t\n\\right)\n\\cos\\left(\n\\frac{\\omega_1+\\omega_2}{2}t\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Coupling Windows.}\n\\begin{equation}\nt_k=\n\\frac{2\\pi k}{|\\omega_1-\\omega_2|}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nFor paired carriers, the raw signal is:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Psi(t)=A\\cos(\\omega_1t)+B\\cos(\\omega_2t).\n\\end{equation}\n\nFor equal or normalized amplitudes, the trigonometric sum identity yields:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Psi(t)\n=\n2C\n\\cos\\left(\n\\frac{\\omega_1-\\omega_2}{2}t\n\\right)\n\\cos\\left(\n\\frac{\\omega_1+\\omega_2}{2}t\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\nEnvelope maxima occur at discrete times:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nt_k=\n\\frac{2\\pi k}{|\\omega_1-\\omega_2|}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nBeat topology identifies discrete envelope windows where coherent coupling is strongest.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
